      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral USART2",
        "description": "Read SVD-decoded USART2 peripheral"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "Multiple probes are attached \u2014 I need to pick the right one.\nThe project targets the NUCLEO-L476RG, so I'll pin its probe:\nRead USART2 live (attach-without-reset, NUCLEO-L476RG probe `066D\u20261514`). Here's what's on the wire:\n\n**USART2 frame config (CR1 = 0x0D, CR2 = 0x0, CR3 = 0x0):**\n\n| Field | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| `PCE` (CR1.10) | **0** | **Parity control disabled \u2014 no parity bit transmitted or checked** |\n| `PS` (CR1.9) | 0 | (don't-care while PCE=0; would be \"even\" if enabled) |\n| `M1:M0` | 0:0 | 8-bit word length |\n| `STOP` (CR2) | 0 | 1 stop bit |\n| `UE/TE/RE` | 1/1/1 | UART enabled, TX+RX active |\n| BRR | 694 | \u2248115200 baud at 80 MHz kernel clock |\n\n**So USART2 is running 8-N-1 @ ~115200.**\n\n- If the host expects **8-N-1** (the usual ST VCP default): yes, it matches.\n- If the host expects **parity (8-E-1 / 8-O-1)**: no \u2014 parity is entirely off (`PCE=0`), so the firmware sends 8 data bits with no parity bit at all. The host would flag parity errors on every byte; to fix it the firmware needs `PCE=1`, `PS` per polarity, and `M1:M0 = 0:1` (9-bit word = 8 data + parity).\n\nSupporting evidence from the status register: `ISR.PE=0` and `FE=0` \u2014 no sticky parity/framing errors latched on the receive side, and `TC=1`/`TXE=1` show the transmitter is idle and healthy. So from the board's perspective nothing it has *received* looks mis-framed either.\n\nIf you tell me what serial settings the host side is opened with, I can give a definitive match/mismatch verdict."
}